I have enough context. The user's `src/env.ts` uses the default `onValidationError`, which t3-env implements as:

```30:33:node_modules/@t3-oss/env-core/dist/index.js
const onValidationError = opts.onValidationError ?? ((issues) => {
    console.error("❌ Invalid environment variables:", issues);
    throw new Error("Invalid environment variables");
});
```

The thrown `Error` message is generic; the specific field info is only in the `console.error` (which is easy to miss in Vite's output). t3-env supports a custom `onValidationError` callback that receives `StandardSchemaV1.Issue[]` — each issue has a `path` (e.g. `["SESSION_SECRET"]`) and `message`. We can format those into the thrown error so the variable name appears directly.

 The default validation error handler just logs the issues to console and throws, but the user can't see which specific environment variables are invalid—either the console output isn't visible in their dev environment or the format isn't clear enough. They need a custom error handler that surfaces the problematic fields more explicitly.

